## Example 3: Global State Store

When state needs to be shared between sections or accessed outside React, use the external store pattern.

**`src/state/counter.ts`**
```ts
import { createExternalStore } from './createStore';

// --- Stores ---
const countStore = createExternalStore<number>(0);

// --- Non-reactive getters (use anywhere) ---
export const getCount = countStore.get;

// --- Setters (use anywhere) ---
export const setCount = countStore.set;

// --- Helper actions ---
export function increment() {
  countStore.set(prev => prev + 1);
}
export function decrement() {
  countStore.set(prev => prev - 1);
}
export function reset() {
  countStore.set(0);
}

// --- Hooks (use in React components only) ---
export const useCount = countStore.useValue;
```

**Using the store in a section:**
```tsx
import { useCount, increment, decrement, reset } from '../../state/counter';

export default function CounterSection() {
  const count = useCount(); // reactive — re-renders when count changes

  return (
    <section className="section-card counter-section">
      <h3>Count: {count}</h3>
      <button type="button" onClick={decrement}>−</button>
      <button type="button" onClick={increment}>+</button>
      <button type="button" onClick={reset}>Reset</button>
    </section>
  );
}
```

**Using the store outside React** (e.g., from a timer callback):
```ts
import { getCount, setCount } from './state/counter';

setInterval(() => {
  const current = getCount(); // read without subscribing
  setCount(current + 1);      // write — triggers re-renders in subscribed components
}, 1000);
```

