## Example 6: Adding a New Page

Pages are full-screen views that replace the showcase flow. They are rendered inside the same viewport and top HUD, but the showcase sections are hidden while a page is active.

### How it works

- **`src/state/page.ts`** — a store holding the active page ID (`"showcase"` = default showcase flow)
- **`src/pages/index.ts`** — a registry mapping page IDs to their React components
- **`src/App.tsx`** — renders the page from the registry, or falls back to the showcase flow

### Step 1: Create the page component

**`src/pages/MyPage.tsx`**
```tsx
import GlueSmallButton from "../components/GlueSmallButton";
import { setPage } from "../state/page";

export default function MyPage() {
  return (
    <div className="tab-content tab-content--page">
      <div className="page-nav">
        <GlueSmallButton onClick={() => setPage("showcase")}>
          Back
        </GlueSmallButton>
      </div>
      <section className="section-card">
        <h3>My Custom Page</h3>
        <p>This is a full-screen page that replaces the showcase.</p>
      </section>
    </div>
  );
}
```

- Use `tab-content tab-content--page` for proper max-width and padding
- Use `page-nav` for a back-button row at the top
- Add any sections or custom content below

### Step 2: Register the page

**`src/pages/index.ts`**
```ts
import type { ComponentType } from "react";
import BuildOrderPage from "./BuildOrderPage";
import MyPage from "./MyPage";

export const PAGE_REGISTRY: Record<string, ComponentType> = {
  "build-orders": BuildOrderPage,
  "my-page": MyPage,  // ← add your page here
};
```

That's it — the page ID `"my-page"` now maps to your component. `App.tsx` looks up the registry automatically.

### Step 3: Navigate to the page

From anywhere in the app (components, callbacks, event handlers):

```tsx
import { setPage } from "../state/page";

// Navigate to your page
setPage("my-page");

// Go back to the showcase
setPage("showcase");
```

You can use any WC3-styled button to trigger navigation:

```tsx
import GlueSmallButton from "../components/GlueSmallButton";
import { setPage } from "../state/page";

<GlueSmallButton onClick={() => setPage("my-page")}>
  Open My Page
</GlueSmallButton>
```

### Step 4 (optional): Read the active page

To conditionally render UI based on the current page:

```tsx
import { usePage } from "../state/page";

function MyComponent() {
  const page = usePage(); // reactive — re-renders on page change
  return <span>Current page: {page}</span>;
}
```

### Existing pages

| Page ID | Component | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `"showcase"` | *(built-in)* | Default showcase flow with all sections |
| `"build-orders"` | `BuildOrderPage` | Full-screen build order tracker |

### Key files

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `src/state/page.ts` | Page store — `setPage()`, `usePage()`, `currentPage()` |
| `src/pages/index.ts` | Page registry — maps IDs to components |
| `src/pages/BuildOrderPage.tsx` | Example full page |

